{"warnings":{"query":{"*":"Formatting of continuation data will be changing soon. To continue using the current formatting, use the 'rawcontinue' parameter. To begin using the new format, pass an empty string for 'continue' in the initial query."}},"query":{"pages":{"6710974":{"pageid":6710974,"ns":0,"title":"Sun Girl (Marvel Comics)","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":":''This article is about the Marvel Comics character Sun Girl. For the DC Comics character of the same name, see ''[[Sun Girl (DC Comics)]]''.''\n{{shortlead|date=July 2014}}\n{{Superherobox| <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=Sun Girl no.1 - August 1948.jpg\n|imagesize = 250\n|converted = y\n|caption=''Sun Girl'' #1 (Aug. 1948). Cover art by [[Ken Bald]].\n|comic_color=background:#ff8080\n|character_name=Sun Girl\n|real_name=Mary Mitchell\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''Sun Girl'' #1 (August 1948)\n|creators=Ken Bald (artist) and unidentified writer\n|alliance_color=background:#cccccc\n|alliances=\n|aliases=\n|powers=Good acrobat<br>Expert martial artist<br>Wields a sunbeam ray gun \n|}}\n\n'''Sun Girl''' is the name of two superheroes from [[Marvel Comics]].\n\n==Publication history==\nThe first Sun Girl was created by artist [[Ken Bald]] and an unidentified writer. She first appeared in ''Sun Girl'' #1 (Aug. 1948), published by Marvel's 1940s precursor, [[Timely Comics]]. Sun Girl starred in a namesake three-issue series cover-dated August to December 1948. She subsequently co-starred in stories of the [[Human Torch (android)|original Human Torch]] in ''The Human Torch'' #32-35 (Sept. 1948 - March 1949), ''[[Captain America|Captain America Comics]]'' #69 (Nov. 1948), ''[[Sub-Mariner Comics]]'' #29 (Nov. 1948), and ''[[Marvel Mystery Comics]]'' #88-91 (Oct. 1948 - April 1949). She additionally starred in a solo story each in the first two of those ''Marvel Mystery'' issues. The Human Torch-Sun Girl story \"The Ray of Madness\" from ''The Human Torch'' #33 (Nov. 1948) was reprinted decades later in Marvel's ''[[Avengers (comics)|Giant-Size Avengers]]'' #1 (Aug. 1974). Sun Girl appears in [[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]] in the final two issues of the four-issue [[miniseries]] ''Saga of the Original Human Torch'' (April\u2013July 1990)\n\nA new Sun Girl debuted in ''[[Superior Spider-Man Team-Up]]'' #1 and will appear as one of the main characters in the upcoming [[Marvel NOW!]] relaunch of the ''[[New Warriors]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/19233-nycc-exclusive-new-warriors-regroup-relaunch-in-2014.html|title=NYCC Exclusive: NEW WARRIORS Regroup, Relaunch in 2014|publisher=Newsarama|date=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n\n===Mary Mitchell===\nA personal secretary for [[Jim Hammond (comics)|Jim Hammond]], the original Human Torch, during the post-war 1940s, Mary Mitchell falls in love with him and becomes his partner as well as his sidekick after [[Toro (comics)|Toro]] leaves to tend to his ailing foster mother.{{issue|date=December 2012}} She fights alongside the Torch until Toro returns and replaced her.{{issue|date=December 2012}} In issue #32 (Sept. 1948), Sun Girl helps the Torch clear the name of an innocent man accused of murder charges, by exposing the real culprit. Later, they convince a retired doctor to perform surgery on a little girl who accidentally swallowed a diamond hidden in a lollypop. Mary leaves to go on her own adventures after that. She occasionally teams up with heroes besides the Torch, such as [[Captain America]]. After Toro returns she resumes her position as secretary and researcher.\n\n===Selah Burke===\n{{Superherobox| <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=Sun Girl Superior Spider-man Team-Up 6.jpg\n|imagesize = 250\n|converted = y\n|caption=''Superior Spider-Man Team-Up' #6<br>(November 2013).<br>Art by [[Marco Checchetto]]<br>Colors by [[Rachelle Rosenberg]]\n|comic_color=background:#ff8080\n|character_name=Sun Girl\n|real_name=Selah Burke\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''Superior Spider-Man Team-Up'' #1 (July 2013)\n|creators=[[Marco Checchetto]] (artist)<br>[[Christopher Yost]] (writer)\n|alliance_color=background:#cccccc\n|alliances=\n|aliases=\n|powers=Proficient engineer<br>Suit with harnesses that enable her to fly and project light blasts<br>Wields dual-wielding pistols and other light-based weaponry\n|}}\n\nA new Sun Girl later appears as one of the heroes temporarily possessed by the [[Carrion (comics)|Carrion]] virus after she came in contact with William Allen. Sun Girl is attacked by [[The Superior Spider-Man]] ([[Doctor Octopus]]' mind in [[Peter Parker]]'s body). The Superior Spider-Man cures Sun Girl of the Carrion virus.<ref>''Superior Spider-Man Team-Up'' #1.</ref> Her identity is later revealed to be Selah Burke, the daughter of [[Lightmaster]] at the time when the Superior Spider-Man made use his Superior Six (consisting of a brainwashed [[Chameleon (comics)|Chameleon]], [[Electro (Marvel Comics)|Electro]], [[Mysterio]]n, [[Sandman (Marvel Comics)|Sandman]], and [[Vulture (comics)|Vulture]]) to combat the [[Wrecking Crew (comics)|Wrecking Crew]]. After the Superior Spider-man fails and the now free Superior Six have captured him and taken hold of a machine that could destroy New York City, Selah manages to save Spider-man and destroy the machine. However, they part in bad terms, Sun Girl thinking that Spider-man is a \"jerk\" due Otto's condescending attitude and insane brainwashing scheme.<ref>''Superior Spider-Man Team Up'' #6.</ref>\n\nSelah next appeared in issue #1 of the 2014 [[New Warriors]] relaunch, helping save the [[Morlocks]] from an attack of the mysterious [[Evolutionaries (comics)|Evolutionaries]].<ref>''New Warriors'' #1.</ref> When offered the opportunity to walk away by these attackers (as they have no intention of going after normal humans), she opts to sacrifice so the mutants can run away. [[Haechi (comics)|Haechi]] steps in and uses his energy absorbing powers to shield her. [[Robbie Baldwin|Speedball]] and [[Vance Astrovik|Justice]] enter the scene which makes the three attackers reevaluate their tactical position and later flee as they were now outnumbered.<ref>''New Warriors'' #2.</ref>\n\n==Powers and abilities==\nMary Mitchell is a good acrobat and is an expert in both Judo and Jiu Jutsu. She also wields a Sunbeam Ray Gun which produces a bright blast of light as well as a lariat which she keeps in her emergency pouch.\n\nSelah Burke is a proficient engineer who creates a suit with a harnesses that grants her flight and the ability to project light blasts. The suit is later modified by the Superior Spider-Man. She also wields dual-wielding pistols capable of firing concussive blasts. She developed and constructed these gear and weapons based on her father's light manipulation technology.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/Mary_Mitchell_%28Earth-616%29 Sun Girl (Mary Mitchell)] at Marvel Wiki\n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/Selah_Burke_%28Earth-616%29 Sun Girl (Selah Burke)] at Marvel Wiki\n\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n[[Category:1948 comic debuts]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1948]]\n[[Category:2013 comic debuts]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 2013]]\n[[Category:Comic book sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Fictional secretaries]]\n[[Category:Golden Age superheroes]]\n[[Category:Timely Comics characters]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics superheroes]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]]"}]}}}}